1. A version control system (VCS) tracks the history of changes made by people, as they collaborate.
Teams can run tests, fix bugs, contribute new code, with the confidence that any code can be reverted.
There are also provisions to keep track of who, when and why changes were made.
2. A distributed version control (DVCS). Collaboration can happen at any time asynchronously.
3. A repository consists of all files and folders of a project along with each files revision history.

